  p.center small-scale
  .notes: :t
    I’ve been suggesting that
    one fundamental, but neglected, feature of humans (and perhaps of other animals)
    is that they are capable of joint action.  And I think that human’s (and perhaps other 
    animals’) social nature depends on their capacity for joint action.
    I’ve also been suggesting that this will be hard to study because there is a lot 
    of quite deep disagreement among philosophers even about where to start.
  .notes: :t()
    The strategy: start with ‘modest socialty’ as Bratman characterises it.
  .slide
    p.handout.notes.show: :t
      Modest sociality: ‘small scale shared intentional agency in the absence of 
      asymmetric authority relations’
    p.right.grey-text Braman 2009, p. 150
    .notes.handout.ctd \citep[p.~150]{Bratman:2009lv}
  .notes: :t
    Why is this a reasonable strategy?  One consideration is that, developmentally and 
    evolutionarily, modest sociality almost certainly came first.  So it is reasonable to 
    hope that if we can understand this, we can build up to more complex cases.
    Another, related thought is Fred Dretske’s maxim that you don’t know how something
    works until you know how to build it.
    It is a reasonable guess that in building agents capable of exercising shared agency,
    a good first target is to get them started with modest sociality.
  .notes: :t
    Note that this is only a starting point: we are also going to consider large scale
    joint actions (like electing a president)
    and very small scale joint actions (like sharing a smile or moving an egg).
    